The SmartSpend budget calculator was developed as a tool to help students manage their 
allowance through an interactive interface. Instead of a traditional 
text-based program, this version uses a Graphical User Interface (GUI) built with Python’s
Tkinter library. This allows the user to see all their spending categories at once and
watch their budget update in real-time as they type.

The process starts with a welcoming interface designed specifically for scholars. To
make the experience easier, the program immediately implements a 10% Savings Rule. 
Before the user even enters a single expense, the code is programmed to automatically 
deduct 10% of the total allowance for savings. This ensures that the student is building 
a financial safety net.

For the Allowance input, we implemented a validation system. Using a validation 
command, the program monitors every key pressed. If a user tries to enter a letter or a 
symbol instead of a number, the code simply blocks the input from appearing. Additionally,
a Try-Except block is used during the final calculation to catch any remaining errors, 
making sure that the allowance is a positive, valid number before any math happens.

When a valid allowance is entered, the student moves to the category section, where they 
allocate percentages for Toiletries, Miscellaneous, Food, and School. To make the app more 
plain-sailing, we used Event Binding. This means that every time the user types a number 
into a category box, the program triggers a Live Update function. This function immediately 
calculates how much of the remaining 90% is left and displays it on the screen, giving the 
user immediate feedback.

A logic check is performed to ensure the budget stays within its limits. Since 10% is 
already saved, the total of the four categories must not exceed the remaining 90%. If a 
student accidentally enters percentages that go over this limit, the Live Update label 
changes to a warning, and the program will show an error message if they try to calculate. 
This 90% Rule keeps the budgeting system consistent and prevents the user from planning to 
spend money they don't actually have.

When the user clicks the "Calculate" button and the percentages are valid, the program 
performs the final math, converting those percentages into actual currency. Any leftover 
percentage is automatically moved into an Emergency Fund, maximizing the student's savings.
Finally, the program uses File I/O to save a permanent record of the budget to a history file 
and displays the results with a typing animation, finishing with a friendly Gamsahamnida to
thank the user.
